{{Infobox book | name = The Varieties of Scientific Experience: A Personal View of the Search for God | image = File:The Varieties of Scientific Experience.jpg | caption = | author = Carl Sagan | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Relationship between religion and science]] | publisher = The Penguin Press HC | pub_date = November 2, 2006 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = 304 | isbn = 1-59420-107-2 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Varieties of Scientific Experience: A Personal View of the Search for God''''' is a book collecting transcribed talks on the subject of [[natural theology]] that astronomer [[Carl Sagan]] delivered in [[1985]] at the [[University of Glasgow]] as part of the [[Gifford Lectures]].<ref>[https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/12/20/carl-sagan-varieties-of-scientific-experience The Varieties of Scientific Experience: Carl Sagan on Science and Spirituality, Brain Pickings]</ref> The book was first published posthumously in 2006, 10 years after his death. The title is a reference to ''[[The Varieties of Religious Experience]]'' by [[William James]].
The book was edited by [[Ann Druyan]], who also provided an introduction section. The sixth chapter, ''The God Hypothesis'', was later reprinted in Christopher Hitchens' anthology ''The Portable Atheist''.
